      "name": "Arctic Bloom",
      "sections": [
        {
          "image": {
            "image": "Sidebar_5_TreasureAndRewards.png",
            "name": "Treasure and Rewards",
            "type": "image"
          },
          "name": "Violet Dusk Poppy Dye",
          "sidebar_heading": "Treasure and Rewards",
          "sidebar_type": "treasure_and_rewards",
          "sources": [
            {
              "link": {
                "alt": "Gatewalkers (Hardcover) pg. 247",
                "aonid": 290,
                "game-obj": "Sources",
                "name": "Gatewalkers (Hardcover) pg. 247",
                "type": "link"
              },
              "name": "Gatewalkers (Hardcover)",
              "page": 247,
              "type": "source"
            }
          ],
          "subtype": "sidebar",
          "text": "Some natives of the Crown of the World hunt yaiafineti matriarchs and harvest their petals, which are used to create an expensive, glimmering violet dye. Although the polyps are far less useful for this purpose, skilled trackers follow their vine tracks back to their matriarch.",
          "type": "section"
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "link": {
            "alt": "Gatewalkers (Hardcover) pg. 247",
            "aonid": 290,
            "game-obj": "Sources",
            "name": "Gatewalkers (Hardcover) pg. 247",
            "type": "link"
          },
          "name": "Gatewalkers (Hardcover)",
          "page": 247,
          "type": "source"
        }
      ],
      "text": "Arctic blooms (also known as yaiafinetis) grow only during periods of extended twilight, thriving across the cold tundra of the Crown of the World exclusively in the winter months. To survive in such harsh conditions, arctic blooms sprout independent polyps called dusk poppies that detach and then creep across the tundra in search of food for their matriarch.   \n  \nDusk poppies sprout from spores that attach to carcasses, but they only blossom during the long twilight unique to the Crown of the World. The perfect conditions for their development are so rare that arctic blooms have developed a vigorous appetite. They feed unceasingly. Much of their energy goes to developing more polyps, and one plant can easily spawn a small infestation of these deadly bulbs.   \n  \nThe plants send out runner shoots that quickly develop purple bulbs. These bulbs, the plant's polyps, sprout many long, hooked vines before detaching from the mother plant. Dusk poppies are short lived but active, foraging for a week or so before they shrivel and die. The poppies aren't dangerous unless handled, as they secrete a fine dust that seizes the nervous system of creatures who come in contact with them.   \n  \n**Paralyzing Poison** (poison) **Saving Throw** DC 19 Fortitude; **Maximum Duration** 6 rounds; **Stage 1** off-guard and clumsy 1 (1 round); **Stage 2** off-guard and clumsy 2 (1 round); **Stage 3** paralyzed (1 round)",
      "type": "section"
    }
  ],
